        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-12-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-11-09T00:00:00-00:44" n="218" subtype="editorial-note"
                type="document" xml:id="d218">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Editorial Note</hi>
                </head>
                <p>In telegram 4192 from Athens, May 31, Minister <persName corresp="#p_YCW1"
                        >Yost</persName> reported that at 5 a. m. that morning several companies of
                    the Greek Army had surrounded the Parliament building and the Athens radio
                    station. <persName corresp="#p_VS1">Venizelos</persName> had called <persName
                        corresp="#p_PMA1">Papagos</persName> who arrived on the scene at 6 a. m. and
                    ordered the troops returned to their barracks which they did. <persName
                        corresp="#p_YCW1">Yost</persName> further reported that an investigation was
                    currently underway to determine who was responsible for this action and whether
                    it was merely an isolated incident. (781.00/5–3151)</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_YCW1">Yost</persName> reported in telegram 4215 from
                    Athens, May 31, that to all outward appearances the situation was calm with no
                    reports of any public or army disturbances in any part of the country. He added
                    that the morning’s incident appeared to be an isolated affair in reaction to the
                    recent resignation of <persName corresp="#p_PMA1">Papagos</persName> as
                    Commander in Chief of the armed forces. (781.00/5–3151) King <persName
                        corresp="#p_PNS1">Paul</persName> described to <persName corresp="#p_PJE1"
                        >Peurifoy</persName> the events and reasons leading to <persName
                        corresp="#p_PMA1">Papagos</persName>’ resignation in an interview on June 4,
                    the substance of which was transmitted by <persName corresp="#p_PJE1"
                        >Peurifoy</persName> to the Secretary in telegram 4272, from Athens, June 4,
                    not printed. (781.00/6–451)</p>
            </div>
